I have made it more than probable, in a former Examen of Steel Waters;
〈…〉 for 1713. p. 249. That Chalybeat Waters do contain ſtiptic and reſtringent Qualities in them, and that they are derived from Iron Minerals, and more particularly the Pyrites, which Doctor Liſter ſuggeſts, (not without Reaſon) to be the Parent of all Iron Oar. I have often examin'd at Deptford the Solution of the Pyrites by Rain Water, out of which Copperas or Vitriol is made, and found it to be a very ſtrong Chalybeat Water: From this Mineral of Iron we have our ſtrong ſtiptic Powders and Waters to ſtop Bleedings, &c. for external and internal
Uſe. A judicious Uſe of Tunbridge and Spa Waters hath cured obſtinate and inveterate Diarraeas, which did not yield to the Force of all other Medicines.
